Tired of failing at your New Years Resolutions?

The statistics are bleak: only 8% of people who make new year‚Äôs resolutions stick to them and those who don‚Äôt usually abandon them after just one week.

Why is this?

People set themselves drastic and unrealistic resolutions that are only sustainable for a month or so at best. 
As a coach, I see it all the time. Right after new year‚Äôs, clients come to me wanting to train 6 days per week, they quit alcohol, cut out food groups and generally punish themselves for their decadence in December.

This quick fix approach to forming good habits is completely unsustainable and often does more harm than good. 
You end up sending a subconscious message to yourself, one that associates a balanced lifestyle with pain and agony. 
You‚Äôre also setting yourself up to fail by doing this, adding a load of unnecessary pressure which can lead to self-hate and more bad habits.

If you want an effective habit-forming strategy, you need to think about small daily changes over a long period. Not only is it more sustainable, it‚Äôs far more enjoyable!

DO YOU WANT TO FIND OUT WHAT THESE SMALL CHANGES ARE, BUT MOST IMPORTANTLY HOW TO IMPLEMENT THEM OVER TIMER?

Wondering what will prevent you from achieving your goals in 2020?

Spoiler: It might not be you!

I remember when I first started to try and turn my life around back in 2013.

My friends actually had a nickname for me ‚Äúparty boy‚Äù ü§£

I slowly started to change my alcohol and eating habits and met fierce resistance and questioning from my friends, colleagues and social group.

Phrases like ‚Äúdon‚Äôt be a pussy‚Äù, ‚Äúyou‚Äôre so boring‚Äù or ‚Äúit won‚Äôt last‚Äù were said to me on a frequent basis.

Fortunately, I didn‚Äôt listen to them. With time I became more confident in myself and what I was trying to achieve, so I carried on.

The same can‚Äôt be said for some clients I have had in the past. Many of them end up quitting their health and fitness journey because they are made to feel so alienated and alone - even from their own families!

You have to understand that your friends or family don‚Äôt realise they are doing this. It‚Äôs a defensive reaction when your own positive actions make them realise their own negative behaviours.

For me, one of the most powerful things I ever did was to stop caring about what other people think about me.

It sounds really simple, but that one small change has had a profound impact on the rest of my life, I wouldn't be where I am today if I hadn't have made that small but powerful change.

Think of it as a skill that you are developing. At first, it will be really hard not to care about what others think, but with time and practice, it will become the norm.

Has anyone here experienced this? It would be great to get your insights and experience so others can learn and make sustainable changes in 2020 üëá

IMPROVE HAMSTRING STRENGTH

The hamstrings play a key part in athletic performance, most noticeably running speed and explosivnes.

Many people still believe that the quads are the most important "speed muscles" in the body. 
This false belief has led to many athletes short-siding their results by becoming excessively quad dominant. 
The true speed muscles are the hamstrings and glutes. Both play a much more important role in the running stride, especially at high velocities.

They are also heavily involved in knee stabilisation, so if you have dodgy knees it might be worth incorporating some of the above exercises.

NOTE: If you do not know how to perform the ‚ÄúHip Hinge‚Äù Only attempt the first exercise - TRX Hamstring Curls. If you don‚Äôt have access to a TRX, a Leg Curl machine can be a great way to start.

Any questions? Leave a comment below.

NO. 1 FAT LOSS MISTAKE

Q. What‚Äôs the number one fat loss mistake I see people making all the time?

A. Thinking that training three times per week makes up for an otherwise sedentary life‚Ä¶

Think about it. The average London commute is 45 minutes, most people will fight for a seat and sit down. 
You then sit in your office for 8 hours, potentially going out to get some lunch, but probably just eating something at your desk.

Then, the 45 minute commute back home where again, you fight for a seat with other commuters. 
What happens at home? You sit down and relax in front of Netflix for two to three hours in the evening, maybe only standing up to make some food, or go and collect your Deliveroo.

That is a total of 12.5 hours of inactivity in your waking day. Three one hour sessions per week is a great starting point, but it‚Äôs only the beginning.

I have been using my @Garmin_Uk watch to track my movement and the amount of calories that I burn on a day to day basis. On a particularly active training day I can burn up to 2000 active calories.

Usually, I burn around 500-700 calories in a workout, so where do the other 1300-1500 come from?

They come from incorporating mini movements throughout the day: ‚úÖ Walk as much as possible throughout the day, and walk FAST!
‚úÖ Take two steps instead of one step on the stairs.
‚úÖ Get off a stop early and walk/jog back to/from work.
‚úÖ Use a public bicycle instead of the train/bus.
‚úÖ Catch up with your friends on the weekend by going for a walk in nature. 
These are just a few ways you can inject more movement into your day and week.

Article: Do you have a growth mindset or a fixed mindset?

Understanding this key question could be the difference in you achieving everything you have ever wanted, or staying where you are and never progressing.

First things first, you must understand what a growth mindset and a fixed mindset are and how they differ before you can establish which is most applicable to your current state of mind. Only after understanding and identifying this, can you then look to improve your mindset and reap the benefits that come with this?

What is a Fixed Mindset?

A Fixed Mindset ‚Äì People with a fixed mindset believe that people are born with a certain amount of intelligence or ability and they can‚Äôt do much to change that. These people focus on looking smart over learning, see the effort as a sign of low ability, and struggle in the face of challenges.

What is a Growth Mindset?

A Growth Mindset ‚Äì People with a growth mindset believe that intelligence and skills can be developed. These people focus on learning over just looking smart, see the effort as the key to success, and thrive in the face of a challenge.

Put simply, both of these types of mindset are the terms used to describe the underlying beliefs people have about learning, ability and intelligence.

What is it about nature that is so rejuvenating?

Some of the scientific research being done about the effect of nature on our bodies and mind may illuminate the reasons. Studies out of Japan show that leisurely forest walks decrease cortisol levels, decrease blood pressure and heart rate, and reduce anxiety. Some Finnish studies show that people receive long-term emotional boosts after spending five hours a month in nature.

Some theorists believe that human beings have a deep-rooted affinity to nature due to thousands of years we spent living in the wild. They suggest we are genetically predisposed to prefer natural environments and in such environments, our bodies function at optimal health and well-being.

It‚Äôs possible, then, that nature invokes some primal, pre-industrial state. Or maybe the inherent beauty of nature relaxes our mind. Perhaps, the fact nature that is untouched (or minimally touched) by human activity has a kind of freedom associated with it.

Another study looked at the dose you need to get the mental health benefits. It seems that 120 minutes of nature time per week is optimal.

Aim to get 20 minutes per day and you will be over this target! Even better, make your nature time #PhoneLess

IMPROVE SQUAT DEPTH!

Full range of motion should be the default for any exercise, particularly the squat. Being able to squat with full ROM and control will improve every aspect of your fitness.

1. Weighted Calf Stretch - Great for improving dorsiflexion and lengthening the muscles in the calf. Probably the most common reason why people can't squat low.

2. Deep Squat Hold - A favourite of mine, make sure you are actively pushing your knees out with our elbows, keeping your spine neutral and your chest facing forward.

3. Cossack Squat - Two variations here, the goal is to lengthen the muscles in the inner thighs so it doesn't matter if you can only manage the easier version. The more flexible you are in this position, the lower you will be able to squat.

4. Heels Raised Weighted Squat - Grab two weight plates and perform squats as low as you can but with your heels raised on each plate. With time you will be able to remove the plates.

For best results, do these exercises before you squat.

WARNING: Being able to full squat may bring about a sense of smugness when you see others half squatting, try not to let it go to your head ü§£. Let me know how you get on and if you have any questionsüëá .

IMPROVE LOWER BACK STRENGTH.
‚Ä¢
Here are three of my favourite exercises to strengthen the lower back, whilst also working on entire posterior chain.
‚Ä¢
I have chosen a beginner, intermediate and more advanced exercise so that you can start working  on your back strength now.
‚Ä¢
For exercises 2 and 3, you must have mastered the hip hinge. I suggest speaking to a Personal Trainer in your gym to teach you how to do it.
‚Ä¢
1Ô∏è‚É£ Arch Body - Aim for maximum contraction and effort along the entire body. Squeeze every muscle in your body, particularly your glutes and upper back muscles. Raise your arms as high as you can, keep your head neutral with your spine.
‚Ä¢
2Ô∏è‚É£ Bent Over Row - Start with light dumbbells or an empty bar. Push your hips back into a hip hinge, whilst maintaining a neutral spine, with a slight bend in your knees. Raise the bar or dumbbells up as if you are trying to pull it through your sternum, lower with control to full extension. Keep your head in line with your spine.
‚Ä¢
3Ô∏è‚É£ Snatch RDL - Grab a bar and hold it with a wide grip. Then rest the bar on your hips. Push your hips back into a hip hinge and allow the bar to travel towards the ground in a straight line, bend your knees very slightly. Go down as low as you can whilst maintaining a neutral spine, do not go down so low and compromise your lower back position. Stand up and squeeze glutes at the tops. The bar should travel straight up and straight down, not forward and back.
‚Ä¢

‚Ä¢
NOTE: Doing these exercises randomly in isolation won‚Äôt do much. Incorporating them into an effective, progressive and consistent strength training program will achieve the best results.
